definition.value: EHNA of absolute configuration 2R,3S. Selective inhibitor of cGMP-stimulated phosphodiesterase (PDE2) (IC50 = 0.8 - 4 mM). Also a potent inhibitor of adenosine deaminase.
EHNA of absolute configuration 2S,3R.
A catalyst that facilitates the migration of a reactant from one phase into another phase where reaction occurs.
A UDP-sugar in which the sugar component is rhamnose.
An aluminium atom having a positive net electric charge.
A transition element cation where the metal is specifed as cadmium.
Chemical role played by a material when used to promote crystallisation.
A carotenol having the structure of 1,1',2,2'-tetrahydro-psi,psi-carotene with hydroxy functions at the 1 and 1' positions.

Any one of a class of di- or tri-block copolymers with a structure consisting of a primary amino group attached to each end of a polyether backbone based on blocks of butylene oxide, propylene oxide or both propylene oxide and ethylene oxide. Molecular weights are typically of the order of 200-4000. The compounds are used in protein crystallisation.

A beta-D-glucoside that is zeaxanthin in which both hydroxy groups have been converted to the corresponding glucosides. It is one of the most polar carotenoids found in nature (solubility in water is 800 ppm, compared with only 12.6 ppm for zeaxanthin itself).
A carboxylic acid anion formed by deprotonation of at least one of the eight carboxy groups of any octacarboxylic acid.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of neurosporaxanthin. The major species at pH 7.3.
The furanose form of L-tagatose 6-phosphate.
A beta-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of beta-alanine.
A member of the class of imidazo[2,1-b][1,3]oxazines in which the hydrogen at position 2 is substituted by a nitro group and in which the oxazine ring is fully saturated.
An L-alpha-amino acid anion that is the conjugate base of L-homocysteine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
Any imidazooxazine resulting from the fusion of the bond between positions 2 and 1 of an imidazole with the bond between positions 2 and 3 of a 1,3-oxazine, and  derivatives.

A member of the class of imidazo[2,1-b][1,3]oxazines resulting from the fusion of the bond between positions 2 and 1 of 1H-imidazole with the bond between positions 2 and 3 of 3,4-dihydro-2H-1,3-oxazine.
An organic salt that is the diammonium salt of L-(+)-tartaric acid.
A citrate salt in which two of the three carboxy groups are deprotonated and associated with ammonium ions as counter-cations.
An organic salt that is the monosodium salt of 2,2'-piperazine-1,4-diylbisethanesulfonic acid (PIPES), a buffering agent.

A praseodymium molecular entity in which a praseodymium(3+) cation is associated with three acetate anions. Used as a heavy atom in protein crystallography experiments (multiple-wavelength anomalous dispersion, multiple isomorphous replacement).
A furan having a nitro group at position 5 and a carboxamido group in turn  bearing a long-chain multifunctional N-alkyl group at position 2.

A glycophytoceramide that consists of phytosphingosine having a 6-acetamido-6-deoxy-alpha-D-galactosyl attached at the O-1 position via a glycosidic linkage and a (Z)-tetracos-15-enoyl group attached to the nitrogen.
An N-[2-hydroxy-5-(1-hydroxy-2-{[1-(4-methoxyphenyl)propan-2-yl]amino}ethyl)phenyl]formamide in which both of the stereocentres have S configuration.
A phenylethanoloamine having 4-hydroxy and 3-formamido substituents on the phenyl ring and an N-(4-methoxyphenyl)propan-2-yl substituent.
A uronoglycosphingolipid where the uronosyl head group is alpha-D-glucuronic acid.
An aroyl group obtained by loss of OH from the carboxy group of purine-6-carboxylic acid.

A glycooctaosylceramide having beta-D-Galp-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcpNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc as the oligoglycosyl component.
A purine derivative that consists of 6-aminohexanoic acid having a purin-6-oyl group attached to the amino function via an amide bond.
A purine derivative that consists of glycine having a purin-6-oyl group attached to the amino function via an amide bond.
An  aromatic amide that is purine bearing a carboxamido substituent at position 6.
An EC 2.4.2.* (pentosyltransferase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of purine nucleoside phosphorylase (EC 2.4.2.1).
Purine bearing a methyl substituent at position 6.
A methyl ester that is purine bearing a methoxycarbonyl substituent at position 6.
A purinemonocarboxylic acid that consists of purine having the carboxy group located at position 6.

A dipeptide derivative that consists of arginylaspartamide having a 2-[(5-sulfo-1-naphthyl)amino]ethyl group attached to the amide nitrogen at the carboxy terminus and a [2-(2-{[4-(indol-3-yl)butanoyl]amino}ethoxy)ethoxy]acetyl group attached to the amino terminus.
A furan having a nitro group at position 5 and a carboxamido group in turn bearing a long-chain multifunctional N-alkyl group at position 2.
A furan having a nitro group at position 5 and a carboxamido group in turn bearing a long-chain multifunctional N-alkyl group at position 2.
A furan having a nitro group at position 5 and a carboxamido group in turn bearing a long-chain multifunctional N-alkyl group at position 2.

A polyether that consists of a poly(ethylene glycol) chain with an indol-3-yl-butanamido group at one end and a multifunctionalised alkyl group, in turn containing nitrofuran and amido moieties, at the other.
A tripeptide that consists of N(6)-lysyl-lysyl-lysinamide where the two side-chain amino functions are acylated by 4-(indol-3-yl)butanoyl and 6-[(5-nitro-2-furoyl)amino]hexanoyl groups.
A phosphonic acid having a 1-hydroxy-2-aminoethyl group attached to the phosphorus.

A tetrapeptide that consists of [(N(6)-lysyl)-N(6)-lysyl]-lysyl-lysinamide where the two side-chain amino functions are acylated by 4-(indol-3-yl)butanoyl and 6-[(5-nitro-2-furoyl)amino]hexanoyl groups.
A furan having a nitro group at position 5 and a carboxamido group in turn bearing a long-chain polyether-based multifunctional N-alkyl group at position 2.

A tripeptide that consists of a glycine residue flanked by two piperidine-4-carboxylic acid units (connected via amide linkages) where the amino terminus is acylated by a 3-[2-(2-{[4-(indol-3-yl)butanoyl]amino}ethoxy)ethoxy]propanoyl group and the carboxy terminus is formally condensed with the amino group of 3-[2-(2-aminoethoxy)ethoxy]propanoic acid, the carboxy group of which is in turn formally condensed with the alpha-amino group of N(6)-5-nitrofuroyllysine.

An ammonium betaine derivative of propanesulfonic acid. One of a group of non-detergent sulfobetaines having a sulfobetaine hydrophilic group and a short hydrophobic group that cannot aggregate to form micelles.
An organofluorine compound formed by substitution of all the methyl protons in propan-2-ol by fluorine. It is a metabolite of inhalation anesthetic sevoflurane.

A dipeptide that consists of two piperidine-4-carboxylic acid units (connected via amide linkages) where the amino terminus is acylated by a 3-[2-(2-{[4-(indol-3-yl)butanoyl]amino}ethoxy)ethoxy]propanoyl group and the carboxy terminus is formally condensed with the amino group of 3-[2-(2-aminoethoxy)ethoxy]propanoic acid, the carboxy group of which is in turn formally condensed with the alpha-amino group of N(6)-5-nitrofuroyllysine.

A tetrapeptide that consists of four piperidine-4-carboxylic acid units (connected via amide linkages) where the amino terminus is acylated by a 3-[2-(2-{[4-(indol-3-yl)butanoyl]amino}ethoxy)ethoxy]propanoyl group and the carboxy terminus is formally condensed with the amino group of 3-[2-(2-aminoethoxy)ethoxy]propanoic acid, the carboxy group of which is in turn formally condensed with the alpha-amino group of N(6)-5-nitrofuroyllysine bearing a polyether moiety at its carboxy terminus.
